Yes. If the app already runs locally, the next move is usually:

push the project to GitHub → connect it to Vercel or Netlify → get an HTTPS link → share it.

For a Vite/React-style app, that is the fastest normal path. Vercel and Netlify both support Vite directly. 

The important catch for your specific app is this:

a shared link does not make MIDI “remote.”
It just lets the other person open the same web app in their own browser. The app will then ask their browser for access to their local MIDI devices via Web MIDI. Web MIDI is only available in secure contexts like HTTPS, and it is still “Limited availability,” so browser support is not universal. 

So the model is:

your app hosted on the web
→ their browser loads it
→ their browser accesses their local MIDI device

Not:

your browser controls their MIDI device over the internet.

For a hackathon-speed workflow, I’d do this:

Fastest deployment path
Put the project in a GitHub repo.

Import that repo into Vercel.

Let Vercel auto-detect Vite and deploy.

Share the generated URL.

Vercel has first-party docs for deploying Vite apps, so this is a clean fit. 

If you prefer Netlify
Same general flow:

Push to GitHub

Connect repo to Netlify

Deploy

Share the URL

Netlify also has official Vite deployment docs and preview URLs. 

What you need to verify before sharing
Your other person will need:

a browser that supports Web MIDI well enough for your app, because MDN still marks it as not Baseline across major browsers, 

