Yes — this is one of the most important ideas in design systems, and you’re right to pause and understand it instead of just doing it mechanically.

The idea is simple:

Don’t assign colors by what they are. Assign them by what they do.

That’s semantic color.

The difference
Raw color (what it is)
Example:

grey/700
This describes:
the pigment

Semantic color (what it's for)
Example:

bg/panel
text/primary
border/default
This describes:
the role

Why this matters (real reason)
Imagine you build your UI using:

grey/800
grey/700
grey/100
Later you decide the app should be slightly lighter.

Now you must:
Find every instance of grey/800 and change it.

Messy.

Now imagine instead you used:

bg/app
bg/panel
text/primary
And those map to grey values:

bg/app → grey/900
bg/panel → grey/800
text/primary → grey/100
If you want a lighter theme:

You change one mapping:

bg/app → grey/800
Whole app updates.

That's the power.

The deeper reason (important)
Semantic tokens separate:

design intent
from
visual implementation

You're saying:

This is a panel background

not:

This is dark gray

That distinction is huge in professional systems.

Think of it like programming
Raw color:

#1F1F1F
Semantic:

panelBackground
Same idea as:

let x = 42   (raw)
let maxUsers = 42   (semantic)
Meaning matters.

