how?

They prevent numbers from “jumping” by making the value field behave like a fixed measurement display, not like normal text.

There are three main tricks DAWs use (Ableton almost certainly uses all three):

1 — Fixed width value area (most important)
Instead of letting text define the width:

They define a fixed box:

[value area: 48px]
Then numbers change inside it.

So:

1
10
100
all sit inside the same width.

In Figma this means:
Value layer → Fixed width
(not Hug).

2 — Right alignment
Numbers usually align right:

   1
  10
 100
This makes the least significant digits stable.

In Figma:
Text alignment → Right

This is standard for:

meters

CC values

dB values

percentages

3 — Tabular numerals (the subtle pro trick)
This is the big one most people miss.

Many UIs use tabular numbers, meaning every digit has the same width.

Normal fonts:

1 is narrow
8 is wide
Tabular:

1 = 8 = 0 width
This prevents tiny shifts when numbers change.

In Figma:
If the font supports it:

Text → Typography → OpenType features → Tabular numbers

(Not all fonts support this.)

What Ableton likely does
Combination of:

fixed width value area
right aligned text
tabular numerals
Result:
Numbers feel mechanically stable.

Why this matters in control UIs
Because jittery numbers feel imprecise.

Stable numbers feel like:
instrument readouts

This is more like hardware design than web design.

How you could structure your slider value
Example:

ValueContainer (fixed width)
    ValueText (right aligned)
Token-wise you could even define:

slider/value-width = 48
slider/value-alignment = right
If you want LLM-describable structure.

The small design principle underneath this
Controls should feel:
mechanical and predictable

Not:
dynamic and fluid (like marketing UI)

That’s why DAWs behave differently from most web apps.

